# Model Versioning Standards

This document defines standards for versioning ML models from development through production.

---

## Version Naming

### Format

```
{model_name}/v{major}.{minor}.{patch}

Example: fraud_detector/v2.1.0
```

| Change Type | Version Bump | Example |
|-------------|-------------|---------|
| New architecture or features | Major (v2.0.0) | Switch from XGBoost to transformer |
| Retrained with new data | Minor (v1.2.0) | Monthly retrain with fresh data |
| Bug fix or config change | Patch (v1.1.1) | Fix preprocessing bug |

---

## Model Registry Workflow

### Stages

```
Development -> Staging -> Production -> Archived
```

| Stage | Purpose | Promotion Criteria |
|-------|---------|-------------------|
| Development | Active experimentation | Any run with logged metrics |
| Staging | Pre-production validation | Passes all validation checks |
| Production | Serving live traffic | A/B test or shadow mode success |
| Archived | Historical reference | Replaced by newer version |

### Promotion Checklist

Before promoting from Staging to Production:

- [ ] Offline metrics meet or exceed current production model
- [ ] Shadow mode comparison shows no regression
- [ ] Latency meets SLA at production traffic levels
- [ ] Memory footprint is within serving budget
- [ ] All governance checks passed (bias, fairness, compliance)
- [ ] Rollback procedure documented and tested
- [ ] Monitoring dashboards updated for new model
- [ ] Stakeholder approval obtained

```python
import mlflow

client = mlflow.MlflowClient()

# Register a new model version
model_uri = f"runs:/{run_id}/model"
mv = client.create_model_version(
    name="fraud_detector",
    source=model_uri,
    run_id=run_id,
    description="Retrained with Q1 2026 data",
)

# Promote to staging
client.set_registered_model_alias("fraud_detector", "staging", mv.version)

# After validation, promote to production
client.set_registered_model_alias("fraud_detector", "production", mv.version)
```

